div.p: Rule resolution: Checks these rules (in order) for the ACEs that it located for the user or group.

span.style: background-color: initial; font-size: 17px;

li.span: If user is admin, then Allow (and stop checking)

ul.li: If there are any Deny entries for the ACEs, then Deny (and stop checking)
Deny takes precedence when a user appears in multiple ACEs in an ACL

span.style: background-color: initial;

li.span: If there is an Allow entry for the user, then Allow (and stop checking)

ul.li: To be allowed access, at least one of the matching entries must specify Allow and none of the entries can be Deny.

span.style: background-color: initial;

li.span: If Inherit from a parent object, check the privileges for the parent object

ul.li: The same process as above is run on the Parent object and recursively goes up the inheritance chain until it reaches the root (Server) or an ancestor ACL where inheritance has been broken.
If Inherit is at the top-level of the chain, then Deny.

span.style: background-color: initial;

li.span: If none of the above, Deny.

span.style: font-size: 17px;

p.style: font-size: 17px; background-color: initial; box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; display: inline !important;

li.p: Dont run processes and jobs as an admin user.

ul.li: Use groups for ACEs instead users.

p.style: font-size: 17px; background-color: initial; box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; display: inline !important;

li.p: Avoid the use of Deny and Break Inheritance

span.style: font-size: 17px; background-color: initial;

li.span: Use Factory Procedures or DSL to maintain ACLs.

p.style: font-size: 17px; background-color: initial; box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; display: inline !important;

span.style: font-size: 17px; background-color: initial;

li.span: Think carefully about what ACLs you are defining, as having thousands of ACLs can become a maintenance issue and introduce performance issues.

span.span: A release contains always pipeline and wraps around additional data and configuration designed for releasing versions of one or many applications --> When a Release is created -> it creates a companion Pipeline (not vicebersa)

li.font: Release can be linked to the Deployment Automation (from CloudBees CD or not)
Releases do not orchestrate the process, the embedded pipeline does this. Parameters are provided to the pipeline

span.span: Releases are designed to represent a deployment of a version of the application or platform and executed through the process to successfully or unsuccessfully complete through to an Environment (For example, "MobileApp Platform version 1.2" is being released into Production).

span.style: border-color: var(--border-color);

span.span: A new patched version of the application should require a new release object to start orchestration of the next version.

li.font: Status: Start (pre-condition), Run (enter parameters), Previos run, Abort All run, End Release

When the pipeline has completed running, it will show if the run completed successfully (pipeline indicated in green) or with an error (pipeline indicated in red). Nevertheless, it requires additionally to be marked asEnd-Release.Then, the pipeline can no longer be run when the release has ended. For example, when the desired application versions have made it to all the desired environments with no compliance issues showing, the release can be ended.

It is an orchestrated set of
Stages(can be skipped and rerunnable): Differentenvironmentsinto which your applications are deployed during your SDLF, such as DEV, QA and Production.

li.span: When a Gate is activated, notification emails are sent to those who are the approvers on manual gate

ul.li: Procedure: Use this option to run a set of best practices, subroutines, modules, or functions that you can create and reuse at the platform level (eg.scripts, command sets, or other automation logic objects.)
Custom: Use this option to define user-defined gate rule conditions (e.gconditions or other command-line entries.)
Pluginsrun third-party procedures that interface with external systems (eg:Selenium automation at the right time by using the Selenium plugin.)

Pipelines are more suitable for re use and re-execution as they may not represent a particular version of the application or platform. They can perform orchestrated processes for almost any purpose, not just for deployments.

span.style: font-family: Arial; background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline;

span.span: Pipelines can be run manually by clicking the run button, triggered automatically by webhooks, polling or by responding to property changes, or scheduled.

span.style: font-family: Arial; background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline;

span.span: Pipelines can also accept parameters that are used as input to the pipeline execution.

ul.li: Limitation:The "Deployer" task in a Pipeline is ineffective. This is due to the deployer task requiring data that is only available in Release objects. This data includes a list of applications to deploy and their associated configurations and environment mapping.

Control: QA
